Project - Customer segmentation to analyze usage behavior for potential credit limit enhancement.¶

The purpose of this project is to identify the right Card Members for a Limit upgradeThe following are the attributes of the dataset CUST_ID : Customer Identification CREDIT_LIMIT : Customer Credit Limit BALANCE : Credit Limit Balance left BALANCE_FREQUENCY : How frequently the Balance is updated (1=frequently,0=not frequently) PURCHASES : Amount of purchases made ONEOFF_PURCHASES : Maximum purchase amount done in one-go INSTALLMENTS_PURCHASES : Amount of purchase done in installment CASH_ADVANCE : Cash in advance taken PURCHASES_FREQUENCY : How frequently the Purchases are made (1=frequently,0=not frequently) ONEOFFPURCHASESFREQUENCY : How frequently Purchases are made in one-go (1=frequently,0=not frequently) PURCHASESINSTALLMENTSFREQUENCY : How frequently purchases in installments are being done (1=frequently,0=not frequently) CASHADVANCEFREQUENCY : How frequently the cash in advance being paid ((1=frequently,0=not frequently) CASHADVANCETRX : Number of Transactions made with "Cash in Advanced" PURCHASES_TRX : Number of purchase transactions made with card PAYMENTS : Amount of Payment paid MINIMUM_PAYMENTS : Minimum amount paid PRCFULLPAYMENT : Percent of full payment paid TENURE : Tenure of credit card service

Descriptive statistics is meant to know how data is distributed.What does descriptive statistics indicates 1. If mean not equal to Median(Q2) indicates the existance of tail. If mean > median, long tail on right side. Skew on right side. If mean < median, long tail on left side. Skew on left side 2. When we observe difference between (Q1,min) and (Q3,max) is not same data is not symmetric meaning If difference between (Q1,min) > (Q3,max) indicates existance of long skewed tail on left side If difference between (Q1,min) < (Q3,max) indicates existance of long skewed tail on right side 3. When we have longs skews, indicates existance of ourliers.

# Function to determine if the given attribute is positively skewed or negatively skewed

def skew(attribute):
    
    mean     = round(credit_feature_df[attribute].mean())
    median   = round(credit_feature_df[attribute].median())
    q75, q25 = np.percentile(credit_feature_df[attribute], [75 ,25])
    
    if  (mean > median):
        print("Positive Right skewed distribution. Median Closure to Q3. Mean > Median")
    
    if  (mean < median):
        print("Negative Left skewed distribution. Median Closure to Q1. Mean > Median")

    if  (mean == median):
        print("Unskewed distribution. Mean = Median")
        
    print("Mean   :" ,mean)
    print("Median :" ,median) 
    print("25%    :",q25)
    print("75%    :",q75)
    sns.distplot(credit_feature_df[attribute],color="Blue",label='Skew = ' + str(round(credit_feature_df[attribute].skew(),3)))
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
    return

def Show(N):
        
    temp = pd.DataFrame(credit_feature_df.nlargest(N, ['PURCHASES'])) 
    
    Cust = list(temp.CUST_ID)
    Pur  = list(temp.PURCHASES)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(30,12))
    barWidth = 0.3
    Number = str(N)   
   
    header = 'High Spending ' + Number + ' Customers'    
    plt.bar(Cust, Pur,color='Blue',width = barWidth)
    plt.title(header,fontsize=30,weight = 'bold')
    plt.xlabel("Customers",fontsize=25,weight = 'bold')
    plt.ylabel("Amount Spent",fontsize=25,weight = 'bold')
    plt.xticks(fontsize=17,weight = 'bold',rotation=0)
    plt.yticks(fontsize=17) 
    plt.grid(False)
    
    # Text on the top of each barplot
    for i in range(N):
        plt.text(x = Cust[i] , y = Pur[i] +7400 ,s = Pur[i], color = 'Black',size = 20,rotation=90)
    
    return

credit_feature_df = credit_feature_df.loc[(credit_feature_df['Utilization'] > 90.00) & (credit_feature_df['PAYMENTS']>(credit_feature_df['CREDIT_LIMIT']*0.9)) & (credit_feature_df['ONEOFF_PURCHASES']>(credit_feature_df['CREDIT_LIMIT']*0.5))]

Use Elbow method to determine the K Value¶

In [642]:
cluster_range = range(1, 15)
cluster_errors = []

for k in cluster_range:
    model     = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(scaled_data)
    labels    = model.labels_
    centroids = model.cluster_centers_
    cluster_errors.append(model.inertia_)  # Cluster errors represents variance between the clusters

plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
plt.style.use('bmh')
plt.plot(cluster_range, cluster_errors,'-o')
plt.xlabel('Number of clusters, k')
plt.ylabel('Inertia')
plt.xticks(cluster_range)
plt.grid(False)
plt.show()

Create model with k=6¶

In [643]:
# Number of clusters
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=6,random_state=148461)
# Fitting the input data
kmeans = kmeans.fit(scaled_data)
# Getting the cluster labels
labels = kmeans.predict(scaled_data)
# Creating new column "CLUSTER" to hold the cluster id
data["CLUSTER"] = labels

Cluster Analysis Summary¶

Observations ------------ CLUSTER 0 :People with average credit limit who make all type of purchases with moderate payment history. Prefer mostly purchase transactions CLUSTER 1 :People with average credit limit who make all type of purchases with moderate payment history.Prefers to take cash advances and make minimum payments CLUSTER 2 :Makes Less purchases having less credit limit and makes moderate payment. Prefer purchase transactions in installments and inclined to one-of-purchases CLUSTER 3 :Group have high number of customers having high credit limit who does high purchases of all types, takes cash advance and makes high payments with minimum due customers CLUSTER 4 :Group have second high number of customers having moderate credit limit who does high purchases of all types and takes high cash advance and makes high payments with minimum due customers CLUSTER 5 :Low spenders with low credit limit with low payment

def pca_fit_transform(df, var = None):
    pca = PCA(var)
    transform_arr = pca.fit_transform(df)
    return pca, transform_arr
